---
/**
 * streaming-event-driven · exactly-once-kafka-deep-dive · Figure 4 — the boundary:
 * inside Kafka EOS holds, outside it doesn't (Level 5).
 *
 * Verbatim from the source HTML (figure + svg + figcaption). Marker refs (#arw,
 * #arwA) resolve against the shared arrowhead <defs> emitted once in the MDX body.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 600 180"
        role="img"
        aria-label="A dashed Kafka boundary contains consume, transaction, and produce; an arrow leaving the boundary to a SQL database, a card charge, and an email is labeled not covered, needs an idempotency key or the outbox pattern."
    >
        <g font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,sans-serif">
            <!-- kafka boundary -->
            <rect
                x="10"
                y="30"
                width="320"
                height="120"
                rx="12"
                fill="#fbfaf2"
                stroke="#2f5d3a"
                stroke-width="1.5"
                stroke-dasharray="6 4"></rect>
            <text
                x="170"
                y="50"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#2f5d3a">INSIDE KAFKA · EOS holds</text
            >
            <rect x="30" y="68" width="80" height="40" rx="8" fill="#fff" stroke="#1f3a5a"
            ></rect><text x="70" y="92" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#1f3a5a"
                >consume</text
            >
            <rect x="130" y="68" width="80" height="40" rx="8" fill="#f1eee2" stroke="#7a1f12"
            ></rect><text
                x="170"
                y="92"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="10"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#7a1f12">txn</text
            >
            <rect x="230" y="68" width="80" height="40" rx="8" fill="#fff" stroke="#2f5d3a"
            ></rect><text x="270" y="92" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >produce</text
            >
            <line x1="110" y1="88" x2="128" y2="88" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
            <line x1="210" y1="88" x2="228" y2="88" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
            <text x="170" y="134" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#6b675f"
                >dedup · atomic offset · fencing</text
            >
            <!-- leaving arrow -->
            <line
                x1="310"
                y1="88"
                x2="380"
                y2="88"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.5"
                marker-end="url(#arwA)"></line>
            <text x="345" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#9a2417"
                >leaves Kafka</text
            >
            <!-- external -->
            <rect
                x="382"
                y="40"
                width="206"
                height="100"
                rx="12"
                fill="#f7ecea"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
            <text
                x="485"
                y="60"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#9a2417">OUTSIDE · NOT covered</text
            >
            <g font-size="9.5" fill="#7a2218">
                <text x="485" y="82" text-anchor="middle">SQL write · charge card · send email</text
                >
                <text x="485" y="100" text-anchor="middle">a crash-and-retry can repeat it</text>
            </g>
            <text
                x="485"
                y="126"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="9.5"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#2f5d3a">→ idempotency key OR outbox</text
            >
        </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        EOS stops at the first byte that leaves Kafka. For that byte you still owe an idempotency
        key or the outbox pattern (Books 1–2).
    </figcaption>
</figure>
